column1: Comparing the Extent and Permanence of Headwater Streams from Two Field Surveys to Values from Hydrographic Databases and Maps
column17:
Supreme Court cases have questioned if jurisdiction under the Clean Water Act extends to water bodies such as streams without year‐round flow. Headwater streams are central to this issue because many are periodically dry, and because little is known about their influence on navigable waters. Maps that include streams regardless of permanence and size will aid regulatory decisions and are fundamental to improving water quality monitoring and models.
This document contains CBI and is not available online or from the EPA Docket Center. Please contact the Document Control Officer listed in the Federal Register

Understanding how Iowans view the benefits and costs of wetlands preservation is key to making decisions about the future of wetlands in Iowa. To that end, the authors created "The Iowa Wetlands Survey." How the survey was designed and administered is described and the results are summarized. The survey reveals important information about how Iowans use wetlands, what they know about wetlands, and how much they value preserving them.

Describes the importance of three main types of Missouri streams: perennial, intermittent and ephemeral. The article also describes threats to streams and best management practices

Prepared by Isabeau Dasho and Bob DiStefano. 
Publish Date: Feb 17, 2011
From the Missouri Conservationist Magazine March 2011 Issue
Missouri Department of Conservation

column1: Estimating the Size and Impact of the Ecological Restoration Economy
column17: This article provides a high-level accounting of the size and scope of the restoration economy in terms of employment, value added, and overall economic output on a national scale. The domestic ecological restoration sector directly employs ~126,000 workers and generates ~$9.5 billion in economic output (sales) annually and supports an additional 95,000 jobs and $15 billion in economic output through indirect (business-to-business) linkages and increased household spending.

column1: The Economics of Environmental Regulation by Licensing: An Assessment of Recent Changes to the Wetland Permitting Process
column17:
Recent changes to the federal wetland permitting process increase the time and effort required of applicants to obtain needed permits. Using a combination of survey and government data, the cost of the reform is calculated at over $300 million annually. This cost is shown to be large relative to the number of wetland acres affected. It is also argued that these changes to the wetland permitting process are inefficient in that they fail to discriminate among wetlands of different quality.
Open Access

column1: Completion of the 2006 National Land Cover Database for the Conterminous United States
column17:
NLCD has been updated to characterize both land cover and land cover change from 2001 to 2006. From ca. 2001 and ca. 2006 land cover remained unchanged for 98.32 percent of the continental United States. The majority of land cover change occurred in the southeastern United States. Deciduous forest, evergreen forest, mixed forest and hay/pasture had the largest net declines. Shrub/scrub and grassland classes had the largest net gains. There were also the expected net gains in developed classes.

column1: Resource quality information and validity of willingness to pay in contingent valuation
column17:
By presenting survey participants with information about four wetlands of varying qualities we test for information effects in a dichotomous choice contingent market for wetlands allocation. Information about quality is a determinant of willingness to pay for wetland preservation. Information about resource quality presented in contingent markets will result in more valid valuations of changes in allocations of environmental resources.

column1: Measuring Contingent Values for Wetlands: Effects of Information About Related Environmental Goods
column17:
This paper estimates willingness to pay (WTP) for preservation of the Clear Creek wetland in western Kentucky when faced with surface coal mining. WTP for preservation of the Clear Creek wetland decreases with information about surface coal mine lake reclamation and, in the initial, independent format increases with information about a nearby publicly owned, wetland area. Lack of explicit information about related environmental goods in contingent markets can contribute to misstatement of WTP.

column1: The Value of Additional Central Flyway Wetlands: The Case of Nebraska’s Rainwater Basin Wetland
column17:
Waterfowl habitat is a biological resource which is neither bought nor sold in the traditional market sense. This study found that Nebraskans positively value their state's Rainwater Basin wetland region in that they are willing to pay to have it maintained and expanded. In addition, this study demonstrates how this value was estimated and
illustrates how such a value can assist in policy decisions regarding habitat acquisition programs.

column1: The Economic Value of Riparian Corridors in Cornbelt Floodplains: A Research Framework
column17:
A new research framework determines the economic value of riparian corridors in floodplains of the agricultural midwest. Market mechanisms traditionally can fail to account for many positive attributes of riparian wetland ecosystems.

column17:

column1: North American Terrestrial Ecoregions: Level III
column17:
Ecoregions are defined in a holistic and comprehensive manner according to a variety of biological, physical and human factors that are found to one extent or another in all natural and human-modified ecosystems across North America. These categories are: 1) Location; 2) Climate; 3) Vegetation; 4) Hydrology; 5) Terrain; 6) Wildlife; and 7) Land Use/Human Activities.

column1: Sensitivity to Scope: Evidence from a CVM Study of Wetlands
column17:
Wetlands valuation is a situation in which CVM studies might be expected to fail scope tests. Theis paper reports results from a split-sample CVM study of Wisconsin wetlands. The survey employed a multiple-bounded, polychotomous-choice format, and compared to WTP distributions using the method of convolutions. The survey demonstrated sensitivity to scope.

column1: Optimal Scope and Bayesian Model Search in Benefit Transfer
column17:
The practice of benefit transfer requires the choice of suitable sources of primary data. The existence of “Golden Rules” notwithstanding, there usually exists limited theoretical guidance for this crucial first step. This chapter illustrates how Bayesian econometric methods can be helpful in identifying the best combination of existing data sources for a given benefit transfer application. This can greatly enhance the robustness and efficiency of transfer estimates.

column1: Measurement, Generalization, and Publication: Sources of Error in Benefit Transfers and Their Management
column17:
This paper offers several means for overcoming measurement errors, generalization errors, and publication bias in benefit transfers including: standardized application of tested methods; closer adherence to benefit transfer protocol; the establishment of an e-journal with explicit criteria for fully recording, reporting, and disseminating research, which has the primary objective of estimating empirical measures of value.

column1: Cross-Context Benefit Transfer: A Bayesian Search for Information Pools
column17:
This paper proposes a Bayesian model search algorithm that examines the probabilities with which two or more sub-sets of meta-data, each corresponding to a different combination of commodity and population, share common value distributions. Exploiting these commonalities leads to substantial efficiency gains for benefit estimates.

column17:

column1: Meta-Analysis and Benefit Transfer for Resource Valuation—Addressing Classical Challenges with Bayesian Modeling
column17:
This study addresses two issues associated with classical meta-regression models. The study illustrates how differences in the available set of regressors across source studies and the treatment of methodological explanatory variables in the construciton of benefit transer models can be addressed efficiently within a Bayesian meta-regression framework leading to a better model fit and tighter welfare estimates for benefit transfer in freshwater angling

column1: Economic Valuation of Some Wetland Outputs of Mud Lake, Minnesota-South Dakota
column17:
The objective of this study was to estimate some economic values of Mud Lake, a managed, lacustrine wetland on the Minnesota-South Dakota border. Several outputs were identified and an economic value estimated for each. These values can assist managers and policy makers in making decisions regarding the opportunity costs of management options or of wetlands alteration and preservation.

column1: Environmental Federalism: Lessons Learned from the Literature
column17:
This review focuses on literature most relevant for the repeal and replacement of the locus of regulatory control of waters under the Clean Water Act. These may include, for example, isolated wetlands completely surrounded by upland, and some ephemeral or intermittent waters. The states will be assumed to gain full regulatory responsibility over these waters. Applicable results derived in other regulatory areas will also be discussed. Report Prepared for EPA's National Center for Environmental Economics. Washington D.C., U.S. EPA NCEE, February 2018
Report EPA Contract No. EP-C-16-020, Work Assignment No. 1-07.

column1: Waters of the United States: Upgrading Wetland Valuation via Benefits Transfer
column17: This study responds to the ongoing debate on the legal protection of wetlands, and the need to understand the benefits created by them. Using updated meta-data on wetland valuation we illustrate how a state-of-the-art meta-regression framework can be adapted to generate BT predictions for incremental changes in wetland acreage over space and time. We apply this framework to generate predicted losses in benefits for realistic changes in wetland acreage for some sub-watersheds.
